9 COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 934, L.D. 1412, “An Act to Increase
10 Contingency Reserves for Maine's Consumer-owned Electric Transmission and
11 Distribution Utilities”
12 Amend the bill by striking out everything after the enacting clause and inserting the
13 following:
14 'Sec. 1. 35-A MRSA §3503, sub-§5, ¶C, as amended by PL 1999, c. 398, Pt. A,
15 §87 and affected by §§104 and 105, is further amended by amending subparagraph (3) to
16 read:
17 (3) To provide for a contingency reserve fund, 1/2 of which may be used for capital
18 purposes, to reflect up to a 25% 35% addition to yearly revenues over the amount
19 required to operate the utility, not including purchased power supply costs, if any.
20 The commission may authorize a utility to establish rates to provide for a
21 contingency reserve fund to reflect an amount greater than a 35% addition to yearly
22 revenues over the amount required to operate the utility. Any surplus in excess of
23 this 25% 35% or the percentage authorized by the commission in accordance with
24 this subparagraph must be used to offset future revenue requirements in the setting
25 of rates. Any interest generated on these funds must be deposited into the
26 contingency reserve fund. The balance in the contingency reserve fund at the close
27 of the utility's fiscal year may not exceed 25% 35% or the percentage authorized
28 by the commission of the yearly revenues over the amount required to operate the
29 utility, not including purchased power supply costs, if any; and'
30 Amend the bill by relettering or renumbering any nonconsecutive Part letter or section
31 number to read consecutively.
32 SUMMARY
3333 This amendment replaces the bill. It increases the amount that a consumer-owned
3344 transmission and distribution utility may keep in a contingency reserve fund to reflect up
3355 to a 35% addition to yearly revenues over the amount required to operate the utility. Like
Page 1 - 132LR0914(02)
COMMITTEE AMENDMENT

COMMITTEE AMENDMENT “ ” to H.P. 934, L.D. 1412
316 the bill, it removes the language that excludes any purchased power supply costs from this
327 formula. It allows the Public Utilities Commission to authorize a consumer-owned utility
338 to keep a contingency reserve fund to reflect an amount greater than a 35% addition to
349 yearly revenues over the amount required to operate the utility.
